The tutorial covers creating a physics world, adding objects like boxes and spheres, and simulating gravity, collisions, and friction. You'll learn how to make objects bounce, slide, and interact with each other in a more realistic way.

Transcript:  
(00:00) \[Music\] physics is the final frontier for building complex 3d games and simulations when i first started learning physics in 3js i struggled a lot i spent a month learning the basics just to make a simple clone of frantic architect i wasn't sure how the physics world worked in relation to the game world which physics library to use or even how to debug my code so in this video we'll go over everything you need to know to get up and running with 3js physics in under 10 minutes let's jump right in \[Music\] so when you work in a game engine like  
(00:36) unity or unreal adding physics to an object is as simple as toggling a button the game engine handles all the complex calculations on the back end and lets us easily tune variables like mass friction or gravity but if you recall from the first tutorial in this series we learned that 3js only helps us render 3d scenes on the web it's not a full-fledged game engine in this case we need to learn how to set up physics in 3js from scratch this is certainly a bit more work but doing so can help us understand the inner workings that these game engines  
(01:09) abstract away from us one of the most confusing aspects of adding physics to a 3js game is that the physics world is separate from the rendered world also known as the game world the 3ds game world is what the user sees it contains stuff like the geometry the shaders the material the objects and everything in between but the physics simulation doesn't need all that information the physics simulation only keeps track of a few critical details like the mass velocity gravity and friction of each object the simulation runs completely separate from  
(01:43) the game world itself our main objective with adding physics will be to keep our 3gs game world in sync with the physics world now the best way to understand this is to just go over an example first we'll need to select a physics library the first library that comes to mind when thinking about physics is mojs this is a direct port of the c plus plus bullet physics library and comes packaged with 3js itself but the main problem with using this library is that it's really hard to set up especially when you're new to physics another  
(02:16) library that comes to mind is rapier it's kind of like the new kid on the block it's built with rust and provides a javascript api with web assembly this library along with ammo js are both good choices if you're building something super performance intensive but let's be real we aren't here to build the next call of duty the main library that i like to use is canon es canon es is a fork of canon js and is maintained by the pomondaris team this is the same team that has already built some really great libraries like react 3 fiber and z  
(02:46) stand i prefer to use this library because it's got great documentation and when any issue comes up i can easily dive into the code after all i'm way more familiar with javascript than i am with c plus or rust and it's pretty easy to set up let's take a look as we do with all our 3ds projects we start with a simple cube on the scene and an access helper from here we're going to start setting up our canon js physics world so in order to set up canon js you're going to have to first npm install it into your project once

In this coding tutorial, we go over a car example in Three.js to get a better understanding of how Cannon.js physics works. We start off by initializing the physics world and adding a rigid vehicle to it. Then we add wheels to the car and ensure that it is moving in accordance with the physics world. After that, we set up event listeners that apply forces to the vehicle based on user inputs. Finally, we sync the Three.js game world with the Cannon.js physics world.

**Youtube Transcript and CommentsThe physics world and the game world are separate entities in 3D game development. The 3D game world is what the user sees and interacts with, containing elements like geometry, shaders, materials, and objects. In contrast, the physics simulation only tracks essential data like mass, velocity, gravity, and friction. It operates independently of the game world.**

**To add physics to a 3js game, you first need to choose a physics library. Options include Ammo.js, Rapier, and Cannon.js. Cannon.js is a popular choice due to its ease of use, good documentation, and familiarity for JavaScript developers.**

**After installing and importing Cannon.js, you initialize the physics world and set parameters like gravity. Objects are added to the physics world as bodies with properties like shape, mass, and position. A ground body, for example, is typically a static plane. To visualize the physics world, you can use the Cannon.js debugger, which creates wireframes around objects.**

**Finally, the 3js game world needs to be synchronized with the physics world. This involves creating 3D meshes that correspond to the physics bodies and updating their positions and rotations in the animate function to match the physics simulation.**  
**The physics world and the game world are separate entities in 3D games and simulations. While the game world includes all the visual elements, the physics world focuses on  mass, velocity, gravity, and friction.**

**Physics libraries**  
There are several JavaScript physics libraries to choose from, including Ammo.js, Rapier, and Cannon.js. Cannon.js is a popular choice due to its ease of use and strong documentation.

**Setting Up Cannon.js**  
To set up Cannon.js, you first need to install it using npm. Then, you initialize the physics world and set parameters like gravity. Objects are added to the physics world as bodies, which have properties like shape, mass, and position.

**Syncing the Worlds**  
To visualize the physics world, you can use the Cannon.js debugger, which creates wireframes around objects. To sync the physics world with the 3D game world, you need to update the position and rotation of the 3D objects to match those of their corresponding physics bodies on each animation frame.

**Building a Car**  
Cannon.js can be used to build complex simulations, such as a simple car. This involves creating a rigid vehicle body, adding wheels, and implementing user controls to apply forces and steering. The car's behavior in the 3D game world is then synced with the physics simulation, resulting in a realistic driving experience.Youtube Transcript and Comments: Three.js \+ Cannon.js Tutorial (part 2/2) |
